    "taxonomy": "Asplenium mohillense is a species of fern in the family Aspleniaceae. It is a member of the genus Asplenium, which comprises over 700 species of ferns. The Asplenium mohillense is further classified as a part of the Asplenium section, which includes several other species of ferns. This classification places it within the larger group of vascular plants, known as the Pteridophyta. Asplenium mohillense is native to Ireland, where it is found growing in damp, shaded areas.",
    "benefits": "Asplenium mohillense has been reported to have potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. The plant is believed to have antimicrobial effects, which may help protect against infections. Some studies suggest that Asplenium mohillense may help to reduce oxidative stress and improve overall well-being. However, more research is needed to confirm its effectiveness and potential therapeutic applications. Further investigation is necessary to fully understand the plant's health benefits and its potential uses in medicine.",
    "parts": "Asplenium mohillense is a species of fern that has been used in traditional medicine. Unfortunately, there is limited information available about the specific medicinal parts of this plant. However, it is often found growing in the same habitats as other species that have been used for medicinal purposes. The rhizomes and fronds of some Asplenium species have been used in traditional remedies. Further research is needed to determine the specific medicinal properties and uses of Asplenium mohillense.",
    "intro": "Asplenium mohillense is a species of fern, specifically a member of the Aspleniaceae family, commonly found in Ireland and the United Kingdom. This fern has been traditionally used in herbal medicine for its potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties, which may aid in wound healing and alleviate symptoms of respiratory issues such as bronchitis and asthma. Bioactive constituents of Asplenium mohillense include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins, which contribute to its medicinal properties. Asplenium mohillense is typically used in herbal preparations such as teas, infusions, and tinctures, as well as in dried form for added convenience."
